concept_explanation.intro:
Reading input in Java involves three pieces:

1. **`Scanner`** — a class that reads from any input source (keyboard, file, string, network).
2. **`System.in`** — the standard input stream. By default, this is the keyboard.
3. **`import java.util.Scanner;`** — Scanner lives in the `java.util` package, so you must import it.

The pattern (memorise this):

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("What's your name? ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");

        sc.close();
    }
}
```

Four lines do the work:
- `Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);` — create a Scanner that reads keyboard input.
- `sc.nextLine()` — read one full line of input (everything the user types until Enter).
- Use the result like any other String.
- `sc.close()` — release the resource when done.

Run that program: it prints `What's your name? `, waits for you to type, then greets you. Your first interactive Java program.

import_explained.intro:
**Why `import java.util.Scanner;`?**

Java's standard library is organized into **packages**. `java.util` is the utility package — it contains Scanner, ArrayList, HashMap, Random, and many other classes you'll use constantly. To use a class from a non-default package, you import it at the TOP of your file (after `public class` is not allowed — imports go above the class).

```java
import java.util.Scanner;  // ← here, at the top

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
    }
}
```

Without the import, the compiler doesn't know what `Scanner` refers to and your code won't compile.

**What's auto-imported?** Only `java.lang` (which contains String, System, Math, Integer, etc.). That's why you've never had to import `String` or `System.out.println`. Everything else needs an explicit import.

reading_strings.code:
import java.util.Scanner;

public class ReadDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your full name: ");
        String fullName = sc.nextLine();   // reads "Aisha Khan" — both words

        System.out.print("Enter one tag: ");
        String tag = sc.next();             // reads only "developer" — stops at space

        System.out.println("Name: " + fullName);
        System.out.println("Tag:  " + tag);

        sc.close();
    }
}

