the_newline_gotcha.the_fix:
**Fix:** call `sc.nextLine()` to discard the leftover newline before reading a real line.

```java
System.out.print("Age: ");
int age = sc.nextInt();
sc.nextLine();   // ← throwaway: consumes the leftover newline

System.out.print("Name: ");
String name = sc.nextLine();   // NOW this waits for real input
```

The throwaway `nextLine()` does nothing visible — it just clears the buffer so the next read works correctly.

**When to add it:** every time you mix `nextInt()`/`nextDouble()`/`next()` with `nextLine()`. Make it a reflex.

**Alternative**: read everything with `nextLine()` then convert manually:
```java
System.out.print("Age: ");
int age = Integer.parseInt(sc.nextLine().trim());
```
This avoids the buffer issue entirely — `nextLine()` always consumes its own newline. Many production codebases use this pattern.

