closing_scanner.try_with_resources:
// Modern style (Java 7+): auto-closes at end of block
try (Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in)) {
    int age = sc.nextInt();
    System.out.println("Age: " + age);
}

step_by_step_solution.details:
Start with the import and the standard structure:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class LoanEligibilityChecker {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Prompts and reads go here

        sc.close();
    }
}
```

The `import` is OUTSIDE and ABOVE the class. The Scanner is created at the top of main.

Ask each question with `print` (so the cursor sits next to the prompt). Use `nextDouble()` for income and credit score, `nextInt()` for age:

```java
System.out.print("Enter your annual income (₹): ");
double income = sc.nextDouble();

System.out.print("Enter your age: ");
int age = sc.nextInt();

System.out.print("Enter your credit score: ");
int creditScore = sc.nextInt();
```

We're only reading numbers — no `nextLine()` here, so we don't have to worry about the newline gotcha YET. But we will the moment we mix in any String input.

Use the conditionals from Topic 4. We'll check each rule separately so we can give a SPECIFIC reason if the user doesn't qualify:

```java
boolean incomeOk = income >= 300000;
boolean ageOk = age >= 21 && age <= 60;
boolean creditOk = creditScore >= 700;

boolean qualifies = incomeOk && ageOk && creditOk;
```

Three booleans, then a final `qualifies` combining all of them with `&&`. Clean.

If qualified, congratulate. Otherwise, list each failed rule:

```java
System.out.println();
System.out.println("=== LOAN ELIGIBILITY RESULT ===");

if (qualifies) {
    System.out.println("\u2705 Congratulations! You qualify for a personal loan.");
} else {
    System.out.println("\u274C Sorry, you don't qualify. Reasons:");
    if (!incomeOk)  System.out.println("  - Annual income below \u20B93,00,000");
    if (!ageOk)     System.out.println("  - Age outside 21-60 range");
    if (!creditOk)  System.out.println("  - Credit score below 700");
}
```

Note the `if (!incomeOk)` etc — only prints the line if THAT rule failed.

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.Scanner;

public class LoanEligibilityChecker {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your annual income (\u20B9): ");
        double income = sc.nextDouble();

        System.out.print("Enter your age: ");
        int age = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter your credit score: ");
        int creditScore = sc.nextInt();

        boolean incomeOk  = income >= 300000;
        boolean ageOk     = age >= 21 && age <= 60;
        boolean creditOk  = creditScore >= 700;
        boolean qualifies = incomeOk && ageOk && creditOk;

        System.out.println();
        System.out.println("=== LOAN ELIGIBILITY RESULT ===");

        if (qualifies) {
            System.out.println("\u2705 Congratulations! You qualify for a personal loan.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("\u274C Sorry, you don't qualify. Reasons:");
            if (!incomeOk)  System.out.println("  - Annual income below \u20B93,00,000");
            if (!ageOk)     System.out.println("  - Age outside 21-60 range");
            if (!creditOk)  System.out.println("  - Credit score below 700");
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}
